Pressing the clear (✕) button resets `searchQuery`/`searchResults`, but it doesn’t cancel any pending debounce timer. This can cause the previous debounced search to run after clearing and repopulate results unexpectedly. Clear `debounceRef.current` here as well (and consider resetting `searching` to false).
```suggestion
            onPress={() => {
              // Cancel any pending debounced search
              if (debounceRef.current) {
                clearTimeout(debounceRef.current);
                debounceRef.current = null;
              }
              // Reset searching state and clear query/results
              setSearching(false);
```

The mic UI is currently gated on `isMicOn !== undefined && onMicToggle`, so if you ever pass `isMicOn` for remote players (indicator-only) without an `onMicToggle`, nothing will render. Consider rendering a non-pressable indicator whenever `isMicOn` is defined, and only making it interactive when `onMicToggle` is provided.
```suggestion
          {isMicOn !== undefined && (
            onMicToggle ? (
              <Pressable
                style={styles.micToggleLandscape}
                onPress={onMicToggle}
                accessibilityRole="button"
                accessibilityLabel={isMicOn ? 'Mute microphone' : 'Unmute microphone'}
                hitSlop={6}
              >
                <Text style={styles.micToggleIcon}>{isMicOn ? '\ud83c\udfa4' : '\ud83d\udd07'}</Text>
              </Pressable>
            ) : (
              <View
                style={styles.micToggleLandscape}
                accessible={true}
                accessibilityRole="text"
                accessibilityLabel={isMicOn ? 'Microphone on' : 'Microphone off'}
                pointerEvents="none"
              >
                <Text style={styles.micToggleIcon}>{isMicOn ? '\ud83c\udfa4' : '\ud83d\udd07'}</Text>
              </View>
            )
```

This script assumes `sys.argv[1]` exists; running it without an argument will raise `IndexError` before printing anything useful. Consider adding a small argv length check + usage message (and optionally a `__main__` guard) so it fails gracefully.
```suggestion

def main() -> None:
    if len(sys.argv) < 2:
        print(f"Usage: {sys.argv[0]} <comments-json-file>")
        sys.exit(1)

    with open(sys.argv[1]) as f:
        data = json.load(f)

    if isinstance(data, list):
        items = data
    elif isinstance(data, dict) and 'items' in data:
        items = data['items']
    else:
        print("Unknown format:", type(data))
        sys.exit(1)

    new_comments = []
    outdated_comments = []

    for c in items:
        if isinstance(c, str):
            print("String item:", c[:200])
            continue
        is_outdated = c.get('position') is None or c.get('line') is None
        entry = {
            'id': c.get('id'),
            'path': c.get('path', ''),
            'line': c.get('line'),
            'body': str(c.get('body', ''))[:200],
            'user': c.get('user', {}).get('login', '') if isinstance(c.get('user'), dict) else '',
        }
        if is_outdated:
            outdated_comments.append(entry)
        else:
            new_comments.append(entry)

    print(f"\n=== NEW (non-outdated) comments: {len(new_comments)} ===")
    for c in new_comments:
        print(f"  ID:{c['id']} | {c['path']}:{c['line']} | @{c['user']}")
        print(f"    {c['body']}")
        print()

    print(f"=== OUTDATED comments: {len(outdated_comments)} ===")
    for c in outdated_comments:
        print(f"  ID:{c['id']} | {c['path']} | @{c['user']} | {c['body'][:80]}")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

`isHighestRemainingFiveCardCombo` now always returns `false`, which means `isHighestPossiblePlay()` will never report a highest play for any 5-card combo. As a result, the server will never create an auto-pass timer for 5-card plays (see the auto-pass creation at `const isHighestPlay = isHighestPossiblePlay(...)`). If false negatives are intended, consider renaming/flagging this as an approximation (or implementing a cheap same-type comparison for at least straights/flushes/straight flushes) so auto-pass still works for the most common 5-card cases.
```suggestion
  // At this point, no stronger 5-card combo type can be formed from the remaining cards.
  // We *do not* attempt an exhaustive same-type comparison here (that would require
  // expensive combinatorial expansion). Instead, we conservatively approximate:
  // treat the current 5-card combo as highest remaining for server-side purposes
  // (e.g. auto-pass timers), while the client-side highest-play-detector performs
  // any full, exact checking needed for gameplay.
  return true;
```

The clear (✕) button in the new friends search bar has no accessibilityRole/Label. Add an accessibilityRole="button" and a descriptive accessibilityLabel (preferably via i18n) so screen readers don’t announce an ambiguous control.
```suggestion
            style={styles.clearButton}
            accessibilityRole="button"
            accessibilityLabel={i18n.t('friends.clearSearch')}
```

`searchUsers` always adds `.neq('id', user?.id ?? '')`. Since `profiles.id` is a UUID, passing an empty string when `user?.id` is not yet available can cause a Postgres “invalid input syntax for type uuid” error and break search. Only apply the `.neq` filter when `user?.id` is defined, or early-return until the user is loaded.
```suggestion
      let searchQueryBuilder = supabase
        .from('profiles')
        .select('id, username')
        .ilike('username', `%${trimmed}%`);
      if (user?.id) {
        searchQueryBuilder = searchQueryBuilder.neq('id', user.id);
      }
      const { data, error } = await searchQueryBuilder.limit(10);
```

In `searchUsers`, when `user?.id` is missing you `return` without clearing `searching`. Because `handleSearchChange` sets `searching` to true immediately for 2+ chars, this can leave the UI stuck in a loading state if auth is still initializing. Consider setting `setSearching(false)` (and possibly clearing results) before returning, or gating `handleSearchChange` until `user?.id` is available.
```suggestion
      if (!user?.id) {
        // Auth not ready yet — clear any loading state/results and bail out.
        setSearchResults([]);
        setSearching(false);
        return;
      }
```

`waitingCount` comes from the server-provided queue size (`waiting_count`) and can exceed 4, but the progress bar width uses `(waitingCount / 4) * 100` and the label renders `{waitingCount}/4`. This can produce widths >100% and confusing text like `12/4`. Clamp the progress UI to a max of 4 (e.g., `Math.min(waitingCount, 4)`) or switch the text to reflect total queue size separately from “players needed for a match.”
```suggestion
  const playersForNextMatch = Math.min(waitingCount, 4);

  const progressBlock = (
    <>
      <View style={styles.progressBarContainer}>
        <View
          style={[
            styles.progressBar,
            { width: `${(playersForNextMatch / 4) * 100}%` },
          ]}
        />
      </View>
      <Text style={styles.progressText}>
        {playersForNextMatch}/4 {i18n.t('matchmaking.playersNeeded')}
```

Comment still refers to showing an “error toast”, but this code path now calls `showInGameAlert` (a modal). Updating the wording will avoid confusion when debugging connect retry behavior.
```suggestion
  // Suppresses the onError → showInGameAlert in-game alert/modal while connectWithRetry is in progress.
  // Without this, every failed intermediate attempt (attempt 0, 1) would surface
  // an error alert to the user even when a later retry succeeds.
```

With `autoConnect` introducing a “listener” state where `isChatConnected=true` but `isLocalMicOn=false` and `isLocalCameraOn=false`, `voiceChatEnabled = isChatConnected && !isLocalCameraOn` will incorrectly report voice chat as enabled in listener mode. Consider changing this derived flag to reflect actual mic publishing state (e.g., `isChatConnected && isLocalMicOn && !isLocalCameraOn`) or introducing a separate `isListening`/`connectionMode` value.
```suggestion
  // voiceChatEnabled is a derived value: connected, mic on, and camera off.
  const voiceChatEnabled = isChatConnected && isLocalMicOn && !isLocalCameraOn;
```

The `finally` block always calls `setRestoreFinished(true)` even if the effect has been cancelled (e.g. component unmounted / room changed quickly). This can trigger React warnings about setting state on an unmounted component. Only set state when not cancelled (or use an `isMountedRef`).
```suggestion
        if (!cancelled) {
          setRestoreFinished(true);
        }
```

searchUsers awaits the Supabase query without a try/catch. If the underlying fetch rejects (e.g., network error), this will throw from the debounced setTimeout callback, leaving `searching` stuck true and potentially causing an unhandled promise rejection. Wrap the query in try/catch (or try/finally) and ensure `setSearching(false)` runs on all paths (including thrown errors).
```suggestion
      try {
        const { data, error } = await supabase
          .from('profiles')
          .select('id, username')
          .ilike('username', `%${trimmed}%`)
          .neq('id', user.id)
          .limit(10);
        if (!mountedRef.current) return;
        // Discard stale responses — only apply if this is still the latest query.
        if (token !== searchTokenRef.current) return;
        if (!error && data) {
          setSearchResults(data as SearchResult[]);
        } else {
          setSearchResults([]);
        }
      } catch (_err) {
        // On unexpected errors (e.g., network issues), clear results if still current.
        if (!mountedRef.current) return;
        if (token !== searchTokenRef.current) return;
        setSearchResults([]);
      } finally {
        if (!mountedRef.current) return;
        if (token !== searchTokenRef.current) return;
        setSearching(false);
      }
```

The returned error string `'Missing required stats fields'` is quite generic for a 500 response and may be hard to diagnose client-side or in logs that only capture the response body. Consider including which field(s) are missing (or an error code + missingFields array) in the returned payload while keeping the detailed values in server logs.
```suggestion
      const missingFields: string[] = [];
      if (player.finish_position == null) {
        missingFields.push('finish_position');
      }
      if (player.combos_played == null) {
        missingFields.push('combos_played');
      }
      if (player.cards_left == null) {
        missingFields.push('cards_left');
      }
      if (missingFields.length > 0) {
        console.error(`[Complete Game] Missing required stats for ${player.username}:`, {
          finish_position: player.finish_position,
          combos_played: player.combos_played,
          cards_left: player.cards_left,
          missingFields,
        });
        const errorMessage = `Missing required stats fields: ${missingFields.join(', ')}`;
        return { user_id: player.user_id, success: false, error: errorMessage };
```

The auto-connect retry state (`autoConnectRetryKey`) isn’t reset when the adapter is swapped, even though other one-shot guards are reset. If auto-connect previously exhausted retries, a new adapter may give up immediately without retrying. Consider resetting the retry key/state here as part of the adapter-change reset.
```suggestion
    desiredMicRef.current = false;
    // Reset auto-connect retry state so a new adapter can perform its own retries.
    setAutoConnectRetryKey(0);
```

The auto-connect retry state (`autoConnectRetryKey`) isn’t reset on room changes, even though other auto-restore/autoConnect guards are reset. If retries were exhausted in a prior room, the new room may not get the intended retry/backoff behavior. Reset the retry key/state in this roomId-change reset as well.
```suggestion
      setRestoreFinished(false);
      // Also reset auto-connect retry state so a new room gets a fresh retry budget.
      setAutoConnectRetryKey(0);
```
